Evaluating small community imitation games¶

In the previous notebook, 4_adding_small_communities.ipynb, we implemented the classes needed to run the community based agent games. We extracted these classes to the communityImitationGameClasses.py file. We will now use these classes to evaluate the found results so that they can be compared to de Boer (2000).

Reference: de Boer, B. (2000). Self-organization in vowel systems. In Journal of Phonetics (Vol. 28, Issue 4, pp. 441465). Elsevier BV. https://doi.org/10.1006/jpho.2000.0125

Table of contents¶

  • Student information
  • Required imports
  • Emergence of a vowel system
    • Emergence from generational system

Setting up the network¶

The below parameters will form the basis of the network structure used.

In [2]:
# Bark operator as used in de Boer (2000)
bark_operator = BarkOperator(critical_distance = 3.5, second_formant_weight = 0.3);

# Community configuration
community_member_amounts = {
    CommunityRole.BABY: 7,
    CommunityRole.STUDENT: 0, # Need to specify so we can update it when there are students
    CommunityRole.DOCTORATE: 2,
    CommunityRole.PROFESSOR: 2,
    CommunityRole.PARENT: 5,
    CommunityRole.GRANDPARENT: 5,
    }

# Community behaviour 
community_behaviours = {
    CommunityRole.BABY: CommunityBehaviour(
      new_sound_prob = 0.03,
      synthesizer = Synthesizer(max_noise_ambient = 0.1, max_noise_agent=0.05),

Emergence of a vowel system¶

Below we will study the emergence of a vowel system for a single simulation.

Emergence from generational system¶

We first test a scenario where there are 2 generations of agents to test an environment where agents are born and killed on generation change. All new agents start from an empty vowel repertoire.

In [3]:
if False: # Use saved result per default
    # Configuring game engine
    category_age_width = 4004 # > 4000 for plotting reasons (i.e. not a new generation of babies on plot)
    iterations = 8000
    
    
    community_game_engine = CommunityGameEngine(community_member_amounts = community_member_amounts,
                                            community_behaviours = community_behaviours,
                                            category_age_width = category_age_width,
                                            iterations = iterations,
                                            bark_operator = bark_operator);

    # Play the game the community game engine was configured for
    checkpoints = [2000, 4000, 6000, 8000];
    game_states = community_game_engine.play_imitation_game(checkpoints);

    # Store result to file
    with open("saved_variables/5/5-sample_game_generations.pickle", 'wb') as f:
        pickle.dump(game_states, f);


    # Delete unused variables
    del category_age_width;
    del iterations;
    del community_game_engine;
    del checkpoints;
    del game_states;
    del f;

Evaluation of the emerged vowel system¶

De boer performed his evaluation using 1000 games for averaging and only 5000 iterations per game compared to the original 10000. It is noted that his figure shows a double average, it averages for example the vowel size for each agent of a game, and then averages those averages to get the total average and standard deviation. The figure thus show the average of the success ratio, sound repetoire size and energy of the agents per game.

Due to limited computational resources we average our extension over 100 trials instead of 1000. We think this is more then reasonable.

In [15]:
if False:
    category_age_width = 4004; # 2 generations
    iterations = 6000; # Stop halfway second generation to limit overfitting
    
    trials = 100;
    results = [None] * trials;
    
    # Perform trials
    for trial in range(trials):
        # Create new game engine
        community_game_engine = CommunityGameEngine(community_member_amounts = community_member_amounts,
                                                    community_behaviours = community_behaviours,
                                                    category_age_width = category_age_width,
                                                    iterations = iterations,
                                                    bark_operator = bark_operator);

        # Only save final result
        checkpoints = [iterations];

        # Save result
        results[trial] = community_game_engine.play_imitation_game(checkpoints)[0];

        # Print progress
        print(f"\nJust completed trial: {trial}", end='\r');

    # Store result to file
    with open("saved_variables/5/5-evaluation_of_emerged_vowel_system.pickle", 'wb') as f:
        pickle.dump(results, f);

    # Delete unused variables
    del category_age_width;
    del iterations;
    del trials;
    del results;
    del trial;
    del checkpoints;
    del community_game_engine;
    del f;

# Get statistics object
statistics = CommunityStatistics(bark_operator= BarkOperator());

# Extract highly educated and regularly educated agents from all agents
results_high = statistics.extract_agents_with_type_from_community_game_states(results, [CommunityRole.DOCTORATE, CommunityRole.PROFESSOR]);
results_regular = statistics.extract_agents_with_type_from_community_game_states(results, [CommunityRole.PARENT, CommunityRole.GRANDPARENT]);

# All (including students, thus expected to be low)
print("avg and std of success ratio (all agents)", statistics.average_agent_success_ratio(results));
print("avg and std of sound size (all agents)", statistics.average_agent_sound_size(results));
print("avg and std of energy (all agents)", statistics.average_agent_energy(results));
print();

# Hihly educated, expected to be relatively close to de Boer 2000
print("avg and std of success ratio (highly educated agents)", statistics.average_agent_success_ratio(results_high));
print("avg and std of sound size (highly educated agents)", statistics.average_agent_sound_size(results_high));
print("avg and std of energy (highly educated agents)", statistics.average_agent_energy(results_high));
print();

# Regularly educated, expected to be slightly poorer
print("avg and std of success ratio (regularly educated agents)", statistics.average_agent_success_ratio(results_regular));
print("avg and std of sound size (regularly educated agents)", statistics.average_agent_sound_size(results_regular));
print("avg and std of energy (regularly educated agents)", statistics.average_agent_energy(results_regular));
print();

Sensitivity to parameter changes¶

Sadly, due to limited computational power the only other experiment we were able to perform is a preliminary study on the acoustic noise impact. It was simply not feasible to run all other simulation like de Boer (2000), as the simulation up untill now already took over 50 computer hours.

Acoustic noise impact¶

To test the impact of the noise parameter we do a preliminary study. This consist of running:

  • 50 trials for the originally used noise levels
  • 50 trials for double the original noise levels
  • 50 trials for triple the original noise levels

50 trials for the originally used noise levels¶

The original noise level trails can be taken from the previous experiment.

In [21]:
if False: # Use previous results by default

    del game_states

    iterations = 6000; # Stop halfway second generation to limit overfitting
    
    trials = 50;
    results = [None] * trials;
    
    # Perform trials
    for trial in range(trials):
        # Create new game engine
        community_game_engine = CommunityGameEngine(community_member_amounts = community_member_amounts,
                                                    community_behaviours = double_noise_community_behaviours,
                                                    category_age_width = category_age_width,
                                                    iterations = iterations,
                                                    bark_operator = bark_operator);

        # Only save final result
        checkpoints = [iterations];

        # Save result
        results[trial] = community_game_engine.play_imitation_game(checkpoints)[0];

        # Print progress
        print(f"\nJust completed trial: {trial}", end='\r');

    # Store result to file
    with open("saved_variables/5/5-noise_triple.pickle", 'wb') as f:
        pickle.dump(results, f);

    # Delete unused variables
    del category_age_width;
    del iterations;
    del trials;
    del results;
    del trial;
    del checkpoints;
    del community_game_engine;
    del f;

noise_parameters = ["Regular noise level", "Doubled noise level", "Tripled noise level"];
filenames = ["regular", "double" ,"triple"]
statistics = CommunityStatistics(bark_operator= BarkOperator());

for i in range(len(noise_parameters)):
    # Get saved experiment result from file
    with open(f"saved_variables/5/5-noise_{filenames[i]}.pickle", 'rb') as f:
        results = pickle.load(f);

    # Extract highly educated and regularly educated agents from all agents
    results_high = statistics.extract_agents_with_type_from_community_game_states(results, [CommunityRole.DOCTORATE, CommunityRole.PROFESSOR]);
    results_regular = statistics.extract_agents_with_type_from_community_game_states(results, [CommunityRole.PARENT, CommunityRole.GRANDPARENT]);

    # Get success, vowel size and energy mean + std for all
    [avg_success, std_success] = statistics.average_agent_success_ratio(results);
    [avg_sound_size, std_sound_size] = statistics.average_agent_sound_size(results);
    [avg_energy, std_energy] = statistics.average_agent_energy(results);

    # Plot Game state with statistics title
    sample = 34;
    results[sample].plot(f"{noise_parameters[i]}, all agents, game {results[sample].iteration}\nAverage success: {avg_success} {std_success}\nAverage energy: {avg_energy} {std_energy}\nAverage sound repetoire size: {avg_sound_size} {std_sound_size}");

    # Get success, vowel size and energy mean + std for highly educated
    [avg_success, std_success] = statistics.average_agent_success_ratio(results_high);
    [avg_sound_size, std_sound_size] = statistics.average_agent_sound_size(results_high);
    [avg_energy, std_energy] = statistics.average_agent_energy(results_high);

    # Plot Game state with statistics title
    results_high[sample].plot_highly_schooled(f"{noise_parameters[i]}, highly educated agents, game {results_high[sample].iteration}\nAverage success: {avg_success} {std_success}\nAverage energy: {avg_energy} {std_energy}\nAverage sound repetoire size: {avg_sound_size} {std_sound_size}");

    # Get success, vowel size and energy mean + std for highly educated
    [avg_success, std_success] = statistics.average_agent_success_ratio(results_regular);
    [avg_sound_size, std_sound_size] = statistics.average_agent_sound_size(results_regular);
    [avg_energy, std_energy] = statistics.average_agent_energy(results_regular);

    # Plot Game state with statistics title
    results_regular[sample].plot_regular_schooled(f"{noise_parameters[i]}, regularly educated agents, game {results_regular[sample].iteration}\nAverage success: {avg_success} {std_success}\nAverage energy: {avg_energy} {std_energy}\nAverage sound repetoire size: {avg_sound_size} {std_sound_size}");
